description: From Middle English dam, from Old English *damm, from Proto-West Germanic *damm, from Proto-Germanic *dammaz.

entries.meaning: A structure placed across a flowing body of water to stop the flow or part of the flow, generally for purposes such as retaining or diverting some of the water or retarding the release of accumulated water to avoid abrupt flooding.
examples: A dam is often an essential source of water to farmers of hilly country.

entries.meaning: The water reservoir resulting from placing such a structure.
examples: Boats may only be used at places set aside for boating on the dam.

entries.meaning: (dentistry) A device to prevent a tooth from getting wet during dental work, consisting of a rubber sheet held with a band.
A firebrick wall, or a stone, which forms the front of the hearth of a blast furnace.

verbs.description: dam (third-person singular simple present dams, present participle damming, simple past and past participle dammed)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To block the flow of water.

description: Variant of dame. Doublet of domina and donna.

entries.meaning: Female parent, mother, generally regarding breeding of animals.
A kind of crowned piece in the game of draughts.

description: Said to be possibly coined from the English phrase "I don't give a dam(n)," referring to its small worth.

entries.meaning: (India) An obsolete Indian copper coin, equal to a fortieth of a rupee.
A former coin of Nepal, 128 of which were worth one mohar.

description: Clipping or Pronunciation spelling of damn.

examples: Do not get too caught up in individual campism. The Most-High sent your spirits back on earth to fix yourselves, come together and wake up our people, so do your dam job and stop letting your fleshly desires control you.
